<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<!-- When creating a new activity, make a copy of this file with appropriate name -->
<worksheet xml:id="compound-1">
  <title>Compound Interest (Not on Quiz)</title>

  <!-- Optional introduction -->
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Suppose we have an account with an initial deposit of $500 and annual interest rate of 12%.  We explore what happens when we compute the interest more than once a year.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose we compute interest twice per year.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              What interest rate should we use to compute the amount of money in our account after <m>\frac12</m> year?  What about when you compute interest again after 1 year?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Compute the amount of money in your account at <m>\frac12</m> year, 1 year, and <m>\frac32</m> year.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Suppose you have <m>A</m> dollars in your account at a certain time.  How much money will you have in <m>\frac12</m> year?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Use what you found in (c) to write your answers in part (a) in a different way.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Use what you found in part (c) to find a formula for the amount of money <m>A(t)</m> you have after <m>t</m> years.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Go through the same process as in #1 to find a formula for <m>A(t)</m> if we compute interest 3 times per year.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find a formula for <m>A(t)</m> if the annual interest rate is <m>r</m> and if we compound interest <m>n</m> times per year.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose you invest $1 at a 100% interest rate for one year.  How much money do you have at the end of the year when you compound it a huge number of times (try a few really big values of <m>n</m>)?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

</worksheet>